    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with CKD</h2>
      <p>CKD is a long game. The cats who do best are usually the ones whose owners learn to track trends, ask specific questions, and push back when they get vague answers. Not because vets are withholding — but because CKD management involves a lot of judgment calls, and your judgment matters too.</p>
      <p>We managed CKD across five cats over many years. Minou had CKD alongside diabetes. Bruce was managed for two to three years before we chose home euthanasia. Yams had CKD alongside stomatitis and hypertension — three conditions pulling in different directions. Milton and Sorbet are both in active management now. What we learned across all of them: the disease rarely kills quality of life on its own. The decisions around it can.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>The framing that helps most:</strong> CKD management is not about returning the kidneys to normal. It is about slowing progression, managing symptoms, and keeping your cat eating and comfortable. Those are different goals — and they change how you evaluate every option your vet presents.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <p>CKD appointments tend to go one of two ways: either you walk out with a clear plan and specific numbers, or you walk out with reassurance and no data. Push for the first.</p>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask for the actual numbers, not the verdict.</strong> "Elevated" tells you nothing you can track. Ask what each value is, what the target is, and what changed since the last visit.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about phosphorus specifically.</strong> It is the most actionable number in CKD and one of the most underemphasised. If your vet hasn't mentioned it, ask for it by name.</li>
        <li><strong>Prioritise eating over dietary perfection.</strong> A cat who won't eat the kidney diet but will eat something else should eat something else. Appetite loss is more dangerous in the short term than the wrong food.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask who is monitoring blood pressure.</strong> Hypertension is common in CKD and causes serious secondary damage. It often goes undetected without explicit testing.</li>
        <li><strong>Name the goal of each treatment.</strong> Is this slowing progression, managing symptoms, or both? If you can't answer that, ask your vet to spell it out.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

