    <section id="resources" class="content-section">
      <h2>Authoritative resources</h2>
      <p>These are the sources your vet is likely referencing. Reading them puts you in the same conversation.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.iris-kidney.com/guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IRIS Staging Guidelines</a></strong> — The international staging framework for feline CKD. This is what your vet uses to categorise severity and guide treatment decisions.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.vet.cornell.edu/departments-centers-and-institutes/cornell-feline-health-center/health-information/feline-health-topics/chronic-kidney-disease" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cornell Feline Health Center — CKD</a></strong> — Accessible, regularly updated overview from one of the leading feline veterinary institutions in North America.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://wsava.org/global-guidelines/global-nutrition-guidelines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WSAVA Nutrition Guidelines</a></strong> — Covers dietary management of chronic disease including kidney disease. Useful context for conversations about prescription diets.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://catvets.com/guidelines/practice-guidelines/chronic-kidney-disease" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AAFP CKD Guidelines</a></strong> — American Association of Feline Practitioners guidelines. A good benchmark for what current standard of care looks like.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

